         "text": "### Patronymics and Surnames\n\nFor a large part of the Middle Ages—a historical period encompassing European history between the years <htdate0> and <htdate1> (<htcite0>)—in the region of the Iberian Peninsula (Portugal and Spain), surnames were not used as they are today. Instead, patronymics were employed, that is, names formed from the father's first name (<htcite1>).\n\nDespite the fact that, today, we see different people using Dias as a surname, it is not possible to claim that they all belong to the same family, as we will see below.\n\n#### The Patronymic\n\nThe origin of the surname Dias as a patronymic becomes evident when analyzing medieval documents. The \"Corónica Navarra\", for example, mentions Rodrigo Díaz, El Cid, as the son of Diego Laínez, grandson of Laín Núñez, and great-grandson of Nuño Laínez (<htcite2>; <htcite3>):",
         "source": [
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "cff9edbf-cd50-44cd-8ef7-54197d68c82b",
               "text": "History Tracers Team",
               "page": "Chronology",
               "date_time": {
                  "type": "gregory",
                  "year": "2024",
                  "month": "-1",
                  "day": "-1"
               }
            },
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "730f0b88-a171-4d7a-805d-de1f3e11203c",
               "text": "Gonçalves, Iria",
