      {
         "text": "Similarly, when analyzing various Portuguese documents, Dr. José Augusto de Sotto Mayor Pizarro presents, in two of his works, several people who signed as Dias and who were the children of a man named Diogo (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\n#### Surnames\n\nThe use of patronymics remained widespread in Portuguese society during the 14th century, according to the Gregorian calendar. In this period, it is possible to verify their use by over 90% of the Portuguese population (<htcite2>).\n\nA significant transition is also observed in this context: patronymics like Dias, which initially indicated lineage, gradually began to be used as hereditary surnames (<htcite3>).\n\n#### Consequences\n\nThe conversion of patronymics into surnames ended up creating a false idea of kinship between people who shared the same last name, leading many to believe they belonged to the same family. To give an idea, in old São Paulo de Piratininga, Américo de Moura identified ten distinct family groups using the surname Dias, with no relation to each other (<htcite4>).",
         "source": [
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "f1c459e5-8007-4554-a835-67c429a04a2e",
               "text": "Pizarro, José A. S.",
